### 🌌 Space Fact of the Day

The **largest volcano in the solar system** is **Olympus Mons** on Mars.

* Height: about **22 km (13.6 miles)** — nearly **three times taller than Mount Everest**.
* Width: roughly **600 km (370 miles)** across.
* It formed because Mars lacks active plate tectonics, allowing lava to build up in one location for millions of years.

Olympus Mons is so large that **astronauts on the surface wouldn’t easily see its full shape because of the planet’s curvature.**

