### 🌌 Space Fact of the Day

**Saturn could float in water—if you could find an ocean big enough.**

Saturn’s **average density is only about 0.69 g/cm³**, which is lower than water (1 g/cm³). This means the gas giant is the **least dense planet in the solar system**.

Of course, Saturn cannot literally float anywhere because no container or ocean large enough exists—but the comparison highlights how **light and gaseous the planet is despite its enormous size**.

